[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Fotello is currently the largest F-stopper sponsor, and they make software for real estate photographers that literally does everything, but most importantly, it will take unedited photos, no matter how bad they are, and create incredible-looking real estate shots automatically. A few weeks ago, I'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'made a video talking about my friend who\'s a realtor who went out and bought a camera, didn\'t know how to use it, accidentally took black photos, and got incredible results with Fotello that were so good that everybody claimed in the comments that the story was made up'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and the results couldn\'t possibly be real, and they forced me to create another video where I proved that this in fact was a real person. A few days ago, the creator of Fotello texts me, and he said, "Lee, I\'ve got a new'

[00:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'feature I want you to check out. We can now make videos from still photos." Now, I have quite a bit of experience in this field, and although AI video is becoming incredible, getting consistent, realistic AI video from stills is still'

[00:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'incredibly difficult. So, I was skeptical, but I said, "Of course, I want to see it. Send me over some examples." And I was blown away. Everything that you\'re seeing right now is generated from real still'

[01:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'photographs. This isn\'t some completely fake AI video with a fake generated house. This is a real location, and all of the details in this home are real. Obviously, I had to try this out for myself, and instead of going out and'

[01:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'taking new pictures where people in the comments would say, "This is fake," I wanted to use the original pictures I took for that original Fotello video with my iPhone. These were taken with my iPhone. Literally, all you have to do is drag the images onto the timeline and'

[01:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'click create video. That\'s it. The software will automatically add movement to still images, or you could combine two images where you start in one place in the room, you manually move, take another picture, and you can put those'

[01:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'together and tell AI, "Start with this image and end on this image," and that\'s going to give you the best results with the most control. Now, the only way to get video that looks like this in the camera, where you have correct lighting inside and outside, is to pump the house'

[01:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'full of light. I have a friend that works for HGTV and they said when they have a video shoot, they have an entire truck of gear and an entire team of people bringing so many'

[02:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'lights inside just so they can balance that indoor light with the outdoor light. No real estate videographer on earth has the time or the money to do anything like that. The reason photos'

[02:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'will always look better than video is because we can spend time editing a photo. We can reveal that blown out window and see the scene outside or we can easily remove that ugly picture frame on the wall. You can\'t do that in video, but if you can do it in stills'

[02:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and then you can create video from those stills, you can have the highest quality video. Now obviously this isn\'t perfect, but it\'s already way better than I expected it to be and it\'s only going to get better from here.'

[02:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'My biggest issue currently with this software is that it has to generate the entire video and you might like everything about it, but there might be one scene that\'s messed up somewhere in the middle and if you want to remove that or you want to try to regenerate'

[02:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it, you have to regenerate the entire video and it\'s going to charge you again. And each time it does, it\'s another 28 bucks. So that\'s going to be expensive. I just called the creator to complain about this and he said, "Lee,'

[03:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'just give me one more week and we\'re going to have an editor and you can trim out sections or fix sections that you don\'t like and that\'s really my only complaint currently. Now like I said, this feature does cost money. It\'s $28 per house per video. But if you create a'

[03:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'free account right now, you can test it out totally for free and it will just watermark the video. And if you already have a paid account, you get three free video creations totally on the house. And stay tuned because in the next week'

[03:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'or two, I\'m going to do a deep dive tutorial video on how to get the best results with this new feature. I am 100% convinced this is the future of real estate and architectural videography. &gt;&gt; Mhm.'
